<HEADLINE>
<P>
DOWNSIDE, UP SIDE OF SINATRA'S LETTER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
So Frank Sinatra (Letters, Sept. 16) doesn't think that stardom is something 
that carries the potential for destruction. Well, Presley, Monroe and Joplin 
are just a few examples of lives botched by the trappings of superstardom. 
</P>
<P>
For Mr. Sinatra to trivialize George Michael's statements and make them seem 
superfluous or self-serving indicate his grasp of the downside of "the 
business" is minuscule. A performer is, foremost, a human being, not a 
commodity, a wind-up toy or machine. 
</P>
<P>
For Michael to see that stardom is robbing him of something meaningful is a 
heartfelt realization, and he deserves a measure of respect for it. 
</P>
<P>
Frank Sinatra, you're one of the best, but you missed the mark in your 
observations about George Michael. 
</P>
<P>
MIKE SEKULIC 
