<P>
LATEST MIDDLE EAST LOTTERY CRAZE: PICK A START DATE FOR WAR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
JIDDA, Saudi Arabia 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Pick the correct date for fighting in the Persian Gulf to break out and you 
could win big money -- if you're one of the American business people in Saudi 
Arabia trying to relieve tensions by holding war lotteries. 
</P>
<P>
The buildup of U.S.-led forces in the gulf has fueled speculation that a clash 
with Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's forces is inevitable. 
</P>
<P>
The lotteries developed because almost every conversation wends its way to that 
topic. 
</P>
<P>
In one such game, players put up nearly $200 to choose a calendar day when 
fighting might erupt. 
</P>
<P>
Heavy favorites so far are concentrated in mid- to late October. Bets for 
November are not yet being accepted. 
</P>
<P>
Players tend to avoid choosing Fridays and Sundays, the Muslim and Christian 
holy days. Many have chosen Mondays. 
</P>
<P>
One group has formed what it calls an Actual Hostilities Committee to determine 
what level of clash is sufficient to qualify for the prize. 
</P>
<P>
This particular group takes into account the possibility of a diplomatic 
solution. 
</P>
