<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Oil island Grissom, one of four just offshore in Long Beach, is centered 
in aerial file photo with downtown marina in background. It symbolizes city's 
extensive tidelands holdings, part of 16-mile-long Wilmington Oil Field, shaded 
in map above, that stretches from Seal Beach to Torrance and has yielded 2.3 
billion barrels in 50 years. RICK CORRALES / Los Angeles Times; Photo, OIL 
SPOILS: The city of Long Beach, local oil men and the state stand to make some 
money off the Persian Gulf crisis as the price of oil doubles. The market is 
fickle, but city officials and private companies are reopening wells. Long 
Beach says its oil revenues could increase by $1.5 million. Worker Greg 
Sherman, above, has a sweeping view of this oil operation on Pier G, as 
reflected in his glasses. J1 ; Table, LONG BEACH CITY OIL REVENUES ; Map, 
Wilmington Oil Field, Los Angeles Times 
</P>
